Gallery Hopping With Julie:
Barkley L. Hendricks
---------------------------

Barkley Hendricks, Untitled (1981)

Barkley Hendricks, Untitled (1981)

The Frick=E2=80=99s show of portraits by Barkley L.
Hendricks, back in the fall of 2023, seemed to flood every art fan=E2=80=99=
s Instagram feed. It was, after all, a watershed moment for Hendricks=E2=80=
=94a Black contemporary artist with a Yale M.F.A. who had died six years pr=
ior at the age of 72. Hendricks=E2=80=99 large-scale, full-length oil portr=
aits of his Black friends and acquaintances are, in some ways, a precursor =
to Kehinde Wiley=E2=80=99s insertion of Black subjects into historic compos=
itions, thereby entering them into a canon from
which they had been largely absent.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The market for these portraits has exploded since Hendricks=E2=80=99 death,=
 with the top 15 prices for his works at auction all achieved in recent yea=
rs. Yocks, a 1975 double-portrait, was sold three times in six years: first=
, in 2017, for $940,000; two years later, for $3.7 million; and for $8.4 mi=
llion after it was included in the Frick exhibition catalogue in
2023. In 2020, one of his works was rumored to have sold on the private mar=
ket for $14 million.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Very few of these grand portraits are left on the market. Hendricks=E2=80=
=99 former gallerist Jack Shainman, who represents the estate, just opened =
an exhibition of the artist=E2=80=99s varied works at his West 20th Street =
location. (The show includes works on paper, photographs, landscapes, and
basketball-themed pieces.) Shainman does have one full-length, partially nu=
de, untitled Hendricks self-portrait from 1981 for sale ( https://jackshain=
man.com/exhibitions/barkley_l_hendricks_spaceistheplace?utm_campaign=3DWall=
+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F10%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBE=
RS+%281%2F10%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm=
_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ). Hendricks demonstrates his sense of humor in =
the painting by depicting himself in an Elizabethan lace collar, cyclops su=
nglasses, and antlers.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The show=E2=80=99s
title, The Space Is the Place, refers to Sun Ra=E2=80=99s Afrofuturist perf=
ormance piece from the 1970s that was eventually turned into a film. The ex=
hibition has a spiritual bent, with many of the works on paper containing i=
mages of moons or solar eclipses. The largest painting, an untitled 5-by-8-=
foot work, shows nine glowing basketballs as phases of the moon. =E2=80=9CI=
t=E2=80=99s a good time for escapism,=E2=80=9D explained curator Elisabeth =
Sann.

Art in the Apocalypse

