argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The Frick=E2=80=99s show of portraits by <stron=
g>Barkley L.
Hendricks</strong>, back in the fall of 2023, seemed to flood <em>every</em=
> art fan=E2=80=99s Instagram feed. It was, after all, a watershed moment f=
or Hendricks=E2=80=94a Black contemporary artist with a Yale M.F.A. who had=
 died six years prior at the age of 72. Hendricks=E2=80=99 large-scale, ful=
l-length oil portraits of his Black friends and acquaintances are, in some =
ways, a precursor to <strong>Kehinde Wiley</strong>=E2=80=99s insertion of =
Black subjects into historic compositions, thereby entering them into a can=
on from
which they had been largely absent.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The market fo=
r these portraits has exploded since Hendricks=E2=80=99 death, with the top=
 15 prices for his works at auction all achieved in recent years. <em>Yocks=
</em>, a 1975 double-portrait, was sold three times in six years: first, in=
 2017, for $940,000; two years later, for $3.7 million; and for $8.4 millio=
n after it was included in the Frick exhibition catalogue in
2023. In 2020, one of his works was rumored to have sold on the private mar=
ket for $14 million.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Very few of these grand por=
traits are left on the market. Hendricks=E2=80=99 former gallerist <strong>=
Jack Shainman</strong>, who represents the estate, just opened an exhibitio=
n of the artist=E2=80=99s varied works at his West 20th Street location. (T=
he show includes works on paper, photographs, landscapes, and
basketball-themed pieces.) Shainman does have one full-length, partially nu=
de, untitled Hendricks self-portrait from 1981 for <a href=3D"https://email=
=2Epuck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVD=
J4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dVVW8yX21ZbVZSb3BL=
