px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Yesterday, as I listened to my Puck partne=
rs <strong>Dylan
Byers</strong> and <strong>Peter Hamby</strong> on <em>The Powers That Be</=
em>, discussing the unreality of the wildfires ripping through Los Angeles,=
 I was struck by a particularly poignant detail. Dylan and Peter, both long=
time Angelenos, were trading stories of disbelief, while analyzing the trag=
ic events through the lens of politics and local media, the latter of which=
 is often underappreciated until a disaster reminds us that it is essential=
=2E=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Dylan relayed the story of a l=
ocal NBC News crew that paused in the midst of its reporting to prevent a d=
istraught homeowner from risking his life by dragging a few possessions out=
 of the fire. =E2=80=9CThis guy went to his house on his bike,=E2=80=9D Dyl=
an recalled, =E2=80=9Cand tried to grab some paintings.=E2=80=9D The man wa=
s determined to carry some very large artworks to safety on two wheels, and=
 the reporter interviewing him offered to take his paintings. As Dylan poin=
ted out,
the news crew understood that the resident and his art had a better chance =
of surviving if the paintings went in the back of their news van and the re=
sident rode out of the fire unencumbered.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">However valua=
ble the paintings may or may not have been is beside the point. When people=
 only have seconds to decide what=E2=80=99s most important to them, they do=
n=E2=80=99t reach for a calculator. When I asked Dylan about the
story, he added that he, too, had evacuated his home with his wife. And whe=
n they left, one of the few things they took with them was a painting, made=
 by a close friend and given to them as a wedding gift. Monetary value isn=
=E2=80=99t, or shouldn=E2=80=99t be, the first thing you consider about a w=
ork of art.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p =
style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">By Wednesday night, most of the art w=
orld had learned from Instagram that former Los Angeles Museum of
Contemporary Art curator <strong>Paul Schimmel</strong> had lost his Altade=
na home of 35 years to the Eaton fire. Given his long tenure, Schimmel=E2=
=80=99s house would have, of course, contained art with both sentimental an=
d historical value. Dealer <strong>John Cheim</strong> also lost his home i=
n Malibu. Cheim had sold some of his most valuable art from his New York ap=
artment at Sotheby=E2=80=99s last year, but surely his Malibu house, too, h=
eld meaningful and valuable objects. <strong>Paul McCarthy</strong>,
<strong>Christina Quarles</strong>,<strong> Ruby Neri</strong>,<strong> Ana=
lia Saban</strong>, and a number of other prominent artists also lost their=
 homes or were evacuated. It=E2=80=99s not clear if their studios were dama=
ged.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;">In each of these cases, the lost art will represent as much =
an emotional dislocation=E2=80=94like the man retrieving his paintings with=
 a bicycle=E2=80=94as it will inflict a monetary or even cultural loss.
Collectors may or may not have good insurance, but <em>no</em> amount of mo=
ney can conjure unique works back from the ashes. As I listened to the podc=
ast, I thought immediately of a friend, a former Los Angeles resident, who =
had recently posted an Instagram video of one of his paintings being instal=
led in the house he rented in the hills above Burbank. Fortunately, it turn=
ed out the video was out of date and the collector had moved out of the ren=
tal some time ago.</p></div>
